The paper deals with the Delaunay triangulation of a set of points in $\mathrm{R}^2$ and introduces a new concept of stable edges in the triangulation. It then defines a new subgraph called the $(c\alpha, \alpha)$-stable Delaunay graph ($\mathrm{SDG}$) and presents a kinetic data structure for maintaining it as the points move. This work involves computational geometry (cs.CG) as it deals with geometric structures and algorithms. The use of a kinetic data structure also suggests a connection to the sub-category of distributed, parallel, and cooperative computing (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the properties of the $\mathrm{SDG}$ and its relationship with the Delaunay triangulation, which falls under the sub-category of graph theory (cs.GR). The use of algebraic trajectories and the analysis of events during motion suggest a connection to the sub-category of control theory (cs.SY) and numerical analysis (cs.NA), respectively.
